### Tested versions

- Tested in Godot v4.4.1.stable.mono

### System information

Godot v4.4.1.stable.mono - Windows 11 (build 26100) - Multi-window, 3 monitors - Vulkan (Mobile) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060 Ti (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.7260) - AMD Ryzen 7 5800X 8-Core Processor (16 threads)

### Issue description

As the documentation states, the `id_focused` signal for a PopupMenu only triggers when the `ui_up` or `ui_down` input actions occur. However, an item can be focused through other means, like mouse enter, which do not cause the signal to fire. This behavior is unintuitive because it differs from other signals that typically are indifferent to how they occur, and is also easy to miss because the signal's name does not imply its conditionallity.

This problem is compounded by the fact that you can call `get_focused_item()` in a `_process()` method and it WILL retrieve the index of an item that is focused via other means, like mouse enter.

There is a work around for this issue by creating your own custom signal, but it feels like this should not be necessary to do and instead just rely on the built in signals. Here is an example of how I'm working around this in C#

```c#
public delegate void PopupMenuIndexFocused(int value);
public event PopupMenuIndexFocused IndexFocused;
private int _focusedIndex = -1;

public override void _Process(double delta)
{
    var focusedIndex = GetFocusedItem();

    if (_focusedIndex != focusedIndex)
    {
        _focusedIndex = focusedIndex;
        IndexFocused?.Invoke(focusedIndex);
    }
}
```

### Steps to reproduce

Create a PopupMenu and try to run code when an item is moused over.

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

Create a PopupMenu and try to run code when an item is moused over.

### Tested versions

- Reproducible in 4.4

### System information

Windows 11, Godot 4.4

### Issue description

I have a scene with relatively simple 3D navmesh on a landscape. Calling QueryPath on mere 200 units hitches the game for 0.5 seconds. In Unreal Engine, significantly more complex navmesh can process about ~10000 path queries in one frame before hitches start to be longer than a duration of the frame.
```
public override bool MoveToLocation(Vector3 Location, Vector3 InStandingDirection, bool AllowPartialPath = true)
	{
		var PathQueryParameters = new NavigationPathQueryParameters3D();
		PathQueryParameters.StartPosition = OwnerUnit.GlobalTransform.Origin;
		PathQueryParameters.TargetPosition = Location;
		PathQueryParameters.SimplifyPath = false;
		PathQueryParameters.SimplifyEpsilon = 1.0f;
		PathQueryParameters.Map = NavigationServer3D.GetMaps()[0];
		var PathQueryResult = new NavigationPathQueryResult3D();
		NavigationServer3D.QueryPath(PathQueryParameters, PathQueryResult);
		if (!IsTargetReachable())
		{
			return false;
		}
		return base.MoveToLocation(Location, InStandingDirection, AllowPartialPath);
	}
```
While I do not expect Godot to always match other engines, performance-wise, 50-100x slower is just way to slow to be able to ship games with this.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Open the repro project
2. Start the game
3. Click in the viewport multiple times

Result: The game hitches every time viewport is clicked (path queries are executed)
Expected: The game does not hitch with just a few path queries on such a simple navmesh

